entry.sense:
[A coll. gen. n.] A certain plant, (Ṣ, Ḳ,) of the kind called HamoDN; (Lth, T, Ṣ;) a leguminous garden-plant; 
n. un. with p {mul-aAHapN}; 
it is a tender plant, with a salt flavour, growing in smooth, or soft, and depressed, tracts of land: (T:) a herb of the kind called HamoD, having twigs and leaves, growing in tracts such as are called qifaAf, of a salt flavour, wholesome to camels and sheep: (M:) a plant like the qul-aAm, in which is a red hue, eaten with milk, bearing grain which is collected like as is that of the fav-, and made into bread, and eaten: so says AḤn, and he adds, I think that it is thus called because of its colour; not because of its taste: and in another place he says, that the mul-aAH is the raceme of the kabaAv of the OaraAk; thus called because of its taste, which is hot, as though containing salt. (M.) [Suœda baccata. Forsk., Flor., 69. (Freytag.)]

hom.sense:
‡ A she-camel that escapes and goes away so quickly that nothing attaches, or clings, to her: (Ṣ:) or quick, or swift, in the utmost degree: (Z, Ḳ:) or quick, or swift; 
as also maluwsN↓: (M:) or the latter signifies a she-camel excellent, or good, in the pace termed Eanaq, 
[so I render miEonaAqN,] that outstrips, and is seen to be first among the camels in the place of pasturage and the watering-place and every journeying. (AZ, Ḳ.*)

